implement a concrete version of this protocol that uses "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresNIO"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To use the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SessionAuthenticator"},{"type":"text","text":" we need to add the "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/HummingbirdAuth\/SessionMiddleware"},{"type":"text","text":". This extracts session id from the request and responds with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"set-cookie"},{"type":"text","text":" headers if the session needs updated. The session middleware converts the session id into an associated session type. In the case of this example the session type consists of two possible authentication states, either "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"authenticated"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"challenge"},{"type":"text","text":". The only challenge available is the TOTP. A user is only considered to be authenticated is the session state is "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"authenticated"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To convert the session state from ","type":"text"},{"code":"challenge","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to ","type":"text"},{"code":"authenticated","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" we have included a ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/auth-otp\/Sources\/App\/Middleware\/TOTPMiddleware.swift","isActive":true},{"text":". This will extract the TOTP token from the request headers and then compare it to the TOTP tokens generated by ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/HummingbirdOTP\/TOTP","isActive":true},{"text":". If one of them is equal then we change the session state to ","type":"text"},{"code":"authenticated","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"RequestContexts","level":3,"anchor":"RequestContexts"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This example uses multiple "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/RequestContext"},{"type":"text","text":". If starts with "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/BasicRequestContext"},{"type":"text","text":" which provides the functionality for a basic Hummingbird application, but does not support authentication or sessions. When we call any route that requires authentication or sessions we convert this context to a "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/auth-otp\/Sources\/App\/RequestContext.swift"},{"type":"text","text":". This conversion is done using "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/RouterMethods\/group(_:context:)-w6fz"},{"type":"text","text":" which creates a new "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/RouterGroup"},{"type":"text","text":" using the new "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"AppSessionRequestContext"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And then in routes that require an authenticated state we have added conversion to an "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"AuthenticatedRequestContext"},{"type":"text","text":" which requires an authenticated identity. This means those routes donâ€™t need to check the authenticated state they are provided with a non-optional identity."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can find out more about "},{"code":"RequestContext","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" transformations in "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/RequestContexts#RequestContext-transformation","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Dynamic HTML","level":3,"anchor":"Dynamic-HTML"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"WebController"},{"text":" generates dynamic content for the logged in screen. It uses ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Mustache","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" to render the content. The mustache templates are stored in the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/auth-otp\/Sources\/App\/Resources","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" folder in the App. The templates are loaded at initialization using ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Bundle.module.resourcePath"},{"text":". The ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"WebController"},{"text":" when rendering the logged in screen extracts information from the authenticated users and uses that as a context while rendering the page mustache template. The resulting output is then wrapped in an ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/auth-otp\/Sources\/App\/Extensions\/html.swift","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" type that conforms to ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/documentation\/Hummingbird\/ResponseGenerator","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" that outputs a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Response"},{"text":" witht eh correct ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"content-type"},{"text":" header.","type":"text"}]}]}],"references":{"doc://com.opticalaberration.hummingbird/documentation/HummingbirdBasicAuth/BasicAu